#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:468
msgid "Suspending Rendering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:470
msgid ""
"To suspend rendering, click the |checkbox| :guilabel:`Render` checkbox in"
" the lower right corner of the status bar. When the |checkbox| "
":guilabel:`Render` checkbox is not checked, QGIS does not redraw the "
"canvas in response to any of the events described in section "
":ref:`redraw_events`. Examples of when you might want to suspend "
"rendering include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:476
msgid "Adding many layers and symbolizing them prior to drawing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:477
msgid ""
"Adding one or more large layers and setting scale dependency before "
"drawing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:478
msgid ""
"Adding one or more large layers and zooming to a specific view before "
"drawing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:479
msgid "Any combination of the above"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:481
msgid ""
"Checking the |checkbox| :guilabel:`Render` checkbox enables rendering and"
" causes an immediate refresh of the map canvas."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:491
msgid "Setting Layer Add Option"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:493
msgid ""
"You can set an option to always load new layers without drawing them. "
"This means the layer will be added to the map, but its visibility "
"checkbox in the legend will be unchecked by default. To set this option, "
"choose menu option :menuselection:`Settings --> Options` and click on the"
" :guilabel:`Rendering` tab. Uncheck the |checkbox| :guilabel:`By default "
"new layers added to the map should be displayed` checkbox. Any layer "
"subsequently added to the map will be off (invisible) by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:507
msgid "Stopping Rendering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:509
msgid ""
"To stop the map drawing, press the :kbd:`ESC` key. This will halt the "
"refresh of the map canvas and leave the map partially drawn. It may take "
"a bit of time between pressing :kbd:`ESC` and the time the map drawing is"
" halted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:514
msgid ""
"It is currently not possible to stop rendering --- this was disabled in "
"the Qt4 port because of User Interface (UI) problems and crashes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:523
msgid "Influence Rendering Quality"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:525
msgid ""
"QGIS has an option to influence the rendering quality of the map. Choose "
"menu option :menuselection:`Settings --> Options`, click on the "
":guilabel:`Rendering` tab and select or deselect |checkbox| "
":guilabel:`Make lines appear less jagged at the expense of some drawing "
"performance`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:534
msgid "Speed-up rendering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:536
msgid ""
"There are some settings that allow you to improve rendering speed. Open "
"the QGIS options dialog using :menuselection:`Settings --> Options`, go "
"to the :guilabel:`Rendering` tab and select or deselect the following "
"checkboxes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:540
msgid ""
"|checkbox| :guilabel:`Use render caching where possible to speed up "
"redraws`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:541
msgid ""
"|checkbox| :guilabel:`Render layers in parallel using many CPU cores` and"
" then set the |checkbox| :guilabel:`Max cores to use`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:543
msgid ""
"The map renders in the background onto a separate image and each "
"|checkbox| :guilabel:`Map Update interval`, the content from this (off-"
"screen) image will be taken to update the visible screen representation. "
"However, if rendering finishes faster than this duration, it will be "
"shown instantaneously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:548
msgid ""
"With |checkbox| :guilabel:`Enable Feature simplification by default for "
"newly added layers`, you simplify features' geometry (less nodes) and as"
"  a result, they quickly display. Be aware that you can also face "
"rendering inconsistencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:558
msgid "Save and Share Layer Properties"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:563
msgid "Managing Custom Styles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:565
msgid ""
"When a vector layer is added to map canvas, QGIS uses by default a random"
" symbol/color to render its features. You can however set a default "
"symbol in :menuselection:`Project --> Project Properties --> Default "
"styles` that will be applied to each newly added layer according to its "
"geometry type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:572
msgid ""
"But, most of the time, you'd prefer to have a custom and more complex "
"style that can be applied automatically or manually (with less efforts) "
"to the layers. You can achieve this goal using the :menuselection:`Style`"
" combobox at the bottom of the Layer Properties dialog. This combobox "
"provides you with functions to create, load and manage styles."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:578
msgid ""
"A style stores any information set in the layer properties dialog to "
"render or interact with the features (including symbology, labeling, "
"action, diagram... settings) for vector layer, or the pixels (band or "
"color rendering, transparency, pyramids, histogram ...) for raster."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:589
msgid "Vector layer style combobox options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:591
msgid ""
"By default, the style applied to a loaded layer is named ``default``. "
"Once you have got the ideal and appropriate rendering for your layer, you"
" can save it by clicking the |selectString| :menuselection:`Style` "
"combobox and choose:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:595
msgid ""
"**Rename Current**: The active style gets renamed and updated with the "
"current options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:597
msgid ""
"**Add**: A new style is created using the current options. By default, it"
" will be saved in the QGIS project file. See below to save the style in "
"another file or a database"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:600
msgid ""
"**Remove**: delete unwanted style, in case you have more than one style "
"defined for the layer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:603
msgid ""
"At the bottom of the Style drop-down list, you see the styles set for the"
" layer and the active one is checked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:606
msgid ""
"Note that each time you validate the layer properties dialog, the active "
"style is updated with the changes you've done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:609
msgid ""
"You can create as many styles as you wish for a layer but only one can be"
" active at a time. Combined to layer visibility preset, this offers a "
"quick and powerful way to manage complex projects with few layers (no "
"need to duplicate any layer in the map legend)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:614
msgid "**Manage styles from layer context menu**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:616
msgid ""
"Right-click on the layer in :guilabel:`Layers Panel` to add, rename or "
"remove layer style."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:623
msgid "Storing Style in a File or a Database"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:625
msgid ""
"While created styles from the :guilabel:`Style` combobox are by default "
"saved inside the project and can be copied and pasted from layer to layer"
" in the project, it's also possible to save them outside the project so "
"that they can be loaded in another project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:631
msgid "Save in plain text file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:633
msgid ""
"Clicking the |selectString| :menuselection:`Style --> Save Style`, you "
"can save the style as a:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:636
msgid "QGIS layer style file (:file:`.qml`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:637
msgid "or SLD file (:file:`.sld`), only available for vector layers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:639
msgid ""
"Used on file based format layers (:file:`.shp`, :file:`.tab`...), "
":guilabel:`Save as Default` generates a :file:`.qml` file along the layer"
" (with the same name). SLDs can be exported from any type of renderer -- "
"single symbol, categorized, graduated or rule-based -- but when importing"
" an SLD, either a single symbol or rule-based renderer is created. That "
"means that categorized or graduated styles are converted to rule-based. "
"If you want to preserve those renderers, you have to stick to the QML "
"format. On the other hand, it can be very handy sometimes to have this "
"easy way of converting styles to rule-based."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:650
msgid "Save in database"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:652
msgid ""
"Vector layer style can also be stored in a database if the layer "
"datasource is a database provider. Supported formats are PostGIS, "
"GeoPackage, SpatiaLite, MSSQL and Oracle. The layer style is saved inside"
" a table (named :file:`layer_styles`) of the database. Click on "
":menuselection:`Save Style --> Save in database` item then fill in the "
"dialog to define a style name, add a description, a :file:`.ui` file if "
"applicable and check if the style should be the default style."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:659
msgid ""
"You can save several styles for a single table in the database. However "
"each table can have only one default style. Default style can be saved in"
" the layer database or in the QGIS local database, a SQLite database in "
"the :file:`~/.qgis2/` directory (where QGIS stores its local settings)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:669
msgid "Save Style in database Dialog"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:671
msgid "**Sharing style files between databases**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:673
msgid ""
"You can only save your style in a database if the layer comes from such a"
" database. You can't mix databases (layer in Oracle and style in MSSQL "
"for instance). Use instead a plain text file if you want the style to be "
"shared among databases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:680
msgid ""
"You may encounter issues to restore the :file:`layer_styles` table from a"
" PostgreSQL database backup. Follow :ref:`layer_style_backup` to fix "
"that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:684
msgid "Load style"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:686
msgid ""
"When loading a layer in QGIS, if a default style already exists for this "
"layer, QGIS loads the layer with this style. Also :menuselection:`Style "
"--> Restore Default` looks for and loads that file when pressed, "
"replacing current style of the layer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:690
msgid ""
"The :menuselection:`Style --> Load Style` helps you apply any saved style"
" to a layer. While plain text file style (:file:`.sld` or :file:`.qml`) "
"can be applied to any layer whatever its format is, loading styles stored"
" in database is only possible if the layer is from the same database or "
"the style is stored in the QGIS local database."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:696
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`Load Style from Database` dialog displays a list of "
"related styles to the layer found in the database and all the other "
"styles saved in it, with name and description."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:700
msgid "**Quickly share a layer style within the project**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:702
msgid ""
"You can also share layer style within a project without importing a file "
"or database style: right-click on the layer in the :guilabel:`Layers "
"Panel` and, from the :guilabel:`Styles` combobox , copy the style of a "
"layer and paste it to a group or a selection of layers: the style is "
"applied to all the layers that are of the same type (vector vs raster) as"
" the original layer and, in case of vector, have the same geometry type "
"(point, line or polygon)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:713
msgid "Color Selector"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:715
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`select color` dialog will appear whenever you push the "
"|selectColor| icon to choose a color. The features of this dialog depends"
" on the state of the :guilabel:`Use native color chooser dialogs` "
"parameter checkbox in :menuselection:`Settings --> Options --> General` "
"menu. When checked, the color dialog used is the one of the OS being "
"used. Otherwise, QGIS custom color chooser is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:722
msgid "**Dynamically change the color with the live-updating option**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:724
msgid ""
"Check the :guilabel:`Use live-updating color chooser dialogs` option in "
"the :menuselection:`Settings --> Options --> General` menu to have the "
"color applied to your items as soon as you pick it in the color chooser "
"dialog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:728
msgid ""
"The custom color chooser dialog has four different tabs which allow you "
"to select colors by |colorBox| :sup:`color ramp`, |colorWheel| "
":sup:`color wheel`, |colorSwatches| :sup:`color swatches` or "
"|colorPicker| :sup:`color picker` (not available under |osx|)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:733
msgid ""
"Whatever method you use, the selected color is always described through "
"color sliders for ``HSV`` (Hue, Saturation, Value) and ``RGB`` (Red, "
"Green, Blue) values. The color is also identifiable as a :guilabel:`HTML "
"notation`. Finally, there is an :guilabel:`opacity` slider to set "
"transparency level."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:738
msgid ""
"Modifying a color is as simple as clicking in the color wheel or ramp or "
"in any of the color parameters sliders. You can adjust such parameters "
"with the spinbox beside or, handy, scrolling the mouse wheel over the "
"corresponding slider. You can also typeset the color html notation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:743
msgid ""
"The dialog also provides a visual comparison between the "
":guilabel:`current` (applied to widget) and the :guilabel:`new` (being "
"selected) colors. Thanks to drag-and-drop, any of these colors can be "
"saved in a slot for an easy access."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:753
msgid "Color selector ramp tab"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:755
msgid ""
"With |colorBox| :sup:`color ramp` or |colorWheel| :sup:`color wheel` tab,"
" you can browse to all possible color combinations and apply it to the "
"item. In the |colorSwatches| :sup:`color swatches` tab, you can choose "
"from a preselected list of color palettes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:760
msgid ":guilabel:`Recent colors`,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:761
msgid ""
":guilabel:`Standard colors`, a user-defined list of colors set under "
":menuselection:`Settings --> Options --> Colors` menu"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:763
msgid ""
"or :guilabel:`Project colors`, a user-defined list of colors set under "
":menuselection:`Project --> Project Properties --> Default Styles`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:766
msgid ""
"The latest palettes can be modified thanks to the |signPlus| and "
"|signMinus| buttons at the bottom of the frame. The :guilabel:`...` "
"button nearby the palette combobox also offers several options to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:771
msgid "copy, paste, import or export colors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:772
msgid ""
"create, import or remove color palettes. Check the :guilabel:`Show in "
"Color Buttons` option to add the custom palette to the color selector "
"widget (see figure_color_selector_)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:781
msgid "Color selector switcher tab"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:783
msgid ""
"Another option is to use the |colorPicker| :sup:`color picker` which "
"allows you to sample a color from under your mouse pointer at any part of"
" QGIS or even from another application by pressing the space bar. Please "
"note that the color picker is OS dependent and is currently not supported"
" by macOS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:790
msgid "**Quick color modification**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:792
msgid ""
"Click the drop-down arrow at the right of the |selectColor| color box "
"button to display a widget for a quick color selection, either in the "
"color wheel or from existing color palettes. You can also use it to "
":guilabel:`copy` or :guilabel:`paste` a color."
msgstr ""

